column25: Dona Ana County International Jetport Airport

column17: The occupant’s improper throttle movement during the start procedure, which resulted in forward movement and loss of airplane control.
The pilot’s improper landing flare, which resulted in a hard bounced landing and loss of control in gusting wind.
The pilot’s inability to find a suitable landing area in a critical fuel situation and his decision to land on a highway, which resulted in the balloon impacting a bridge railing and terrain.

The pilot’s failure to follow the go-around procedures by prematurely retracting the flaps and not establishing a proper go-around climb speed after attempting to land with a quartering tailwind, resulting in the airplane’s inability to climb.
The pilot’s failure to maintain the proper descent rate during the balloon’s approach to landing, which resulted in a hard landing and serious passenger injury.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control and the flight instructor's inadequate remedial action during the landing roll, which resulted in a ground loop.
The pilot’s failure to extend the landing gear before landing due to a distraction, which resulted in an impact with the runway.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll in gusting wind.

The total loss of engine power due to the fatigue failure of the starter-generator input (zerol) gear which failed due to poor maintenance. Contributing to the accident was the unsuccessful autorotation complicated by the setting sun and high density altitude.
The pilot’s decision to land on an unsuitable surface which resulted in his loss of aircraft control.
The pilot’s loss of airplane control during takeoff following an encounter with a gust of wind.
The pilot’s failure to maintain airspeed and rotor rpm which resulted in a hard landing.
A loss of control while maneuvering at a high-density altitude in gusty wind conditions.
The pilot’s loss of control of the airplane after the inadvertent unlocking and opening of the canopy for reasons that could not be determined based on available evidence.

The airplane’s inability to climb during takeoff due to a degradation of engine performance due to high density altitude. Contributing to the accident was the pilot’s decision to continue the takeoff.
The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll.
The pilot’s failure to adequately monitor the environment during a low level operation, which resulted in collision with vegetation.
The pilot's failure to maintain separation from an FM tower guy wire while on an aerial survey flight.
The pilot’s inadequate fuel management which resulted in a total loss of engine power due to fuel starvation.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control during takeoff.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control during a landing roll, which resulted in a ground loop and impact with the ground.
The pilot’s failure to maintain clearance from terrain while maneuvering at a low altitude. Contributing to the accident was the pilot’s reduced forward visibility due to the sun.
The pilot’s failure to maintain the proper descent rate during the balloon’s approach to landing, which resulted in a hard landing and serious passenger injury.
The pilot’s improper landing flare which resulted in a hard and bounced landing.
The failure of the nose gear hydraulic flex line, which resulted in a loss of hydraulic fluid which prevented the main landing gear from fully extending and locking into place during landing.
A loss of engine performance due to lead fouling of the lower spark plugs, which resulted in an off airport forced landing.
The pilot's failure to maintain adequate clearance from a windmill while maneuvering during an aerial application flight.
The failure of the pilot to maintain adequate clearance from power lines while maneuvering for landing. Contributing to the accident was the pilot’s use of impairing, illicit drugs.
The pilot's failure to maintain lateral control during takeoff after an encounter with a gusting wind, which resulted in a wing strike.

A leak in the oil line that supplied the engine with oil, which resulted in oil exhaustion and the total loss of engine power.  Contributing to the accident was the routing of the oil line to close to the exhaust manifold.
The pilot’s loss of situational awareness and failure to touchdown on the runway which resulted in a collision with the airport’s perimeter fence.
The pilot’s delayed use in the operation of carburetor heat which resulted in a loss of engine power due to carburetor icing.

The pilot’s failure to maintain the proper descent rate during the balloon’s approach to landing, which resulted in a hard landing and fatal passenger injury when the passenger fell out of the basket.
The pilot’s failure to maintain sufficient altitude above terrain while operating in reduced visibility due to snow showers.
The pilot’s failure to extend the landing gear, which resulted in the airplane landing with the landing gear retracted.
The pilot’s failure to maintain lateral control during initial climb due to distraction, which resulted in an in-flight upset and impact with terrain.
The pilot’s failure to maintain the proper descent rate during the balloon’s approach to a high-wind landing, which resulted in a hard landing and serious passenger injury.

The total loss of power in the right engine due to fuel starvation. Contributing to the accident was the pilot’s failure to follow the manufacturer-recommended procedure after the loss of power in the right engine.

The pilot's improper landing flare which resulted in a hard, bounced landing, and subsequent runway excursion. Contributing to the accident was the airplane’s aft center of gravity at the time of the accident.
The pilots precautionary off airport landing due to an undetermined engine issue.
A partial loss of engine power due to fuel starvation, which likely resulted from a leak in the fuel system.
A burner flameout, which resulted in the pilot's inability to arrest the balloon’s descent and its subsequent impact with power lines as he was trying to relight the burner.

The pilot receiving instruction's failure to maintain directional control and his inadvertent left brake pedal application during the landing roll, which resulted in a runway excursion and ground-loop.

The airplane’s degraded performance due to high-density altitude and gusting wind conditions, which resulted in its inability to maintain altitude during the initial takeoff climb. Contributing to the accident was the pilot’s lack of experience with high altitude flying and his decision to depart in high-density altitude and gusting wind conditions.
The pilot's failure maintain clearance from power lines, which resulted in an explosion and preimpact fire.
The pilot's failure to maintain an adequate descent rate during landing, which resulted in a hard landing and a postaccident fire.
The pilot's decision to fly into terrain that exceeded the performance capabilities of the airplane, which resulted in failure to maintain clearance from trees and terrain.
The in-flight separation of a section of a propeller blade due to a fatigue crack, which resulted in a forced landing.
The pilot's improper preflight performance planning for a high-density altitude takeoff from a short, dirt airstrip, which resulted in impact with terrain.

The airplane’s inability to maintain altitude during the initial climb due to a degradation in the airplane’s performance as a result of high-density altitude conditions at the time of takeoff. Contributing to the accident were the pilot’s inadequate preflight performance planning calculations.
An in-flight cardiac event which necessitated an emergency landing, and which the pilot succumbed to.
The pilot's improper landing flare in gusting wind conditions, which resulted in a hard landing.
The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during landing with a crosswind, which resulted in a wing strike.
The pilot's failure to maintain airplane control while landing with a quartering tailwind.

The pilot's loss of airplane control due to his failure to maintain appropriate control inputs and airspeed after shutting down an engine because of a progressive failure of the pressure relief valve in the fuel pump, which resulted in variable fuel pressure in the engine. Contributing to the loss of control was the pilot's use of multiple impairing medications.

The flight instructor’s failure to maintain adequate airspeed during the initial climb after takeoff, which resulted in an exceedance of the airplane's critical angle of attack, an aerodynamic stall, and loss of control.

The noninstrument-rated pilot's continued visual flight rules flight into an area of forecast instrument meteorological conditions, which resulted in spatial disorientation and a subsequent loss of control.
The pilot’s failure to properly position the fuel selector before takeoff, which resulted in a total loss of engine power due to fuel starvation.
A loss of control for reasons that could not be determined based on available evidence.
The pilot's failure to maintain adequate main rotor speed while the helicopter was in an out-of-ground effect hover.
The pilot's improper landing flare, which resulted in hard, bounced landing, loss of directional control, runway excursion, and impact with a fence and terrain during an attempted go-around.
